4:
Looks like things are weirdly quiet
around here too...
7:
It's as if the town has died off... A
plague, perhaps.
22:
Haha... Does it look like I am?
*cough* *cough*
24:
Damn it... Can't believe I got infected
too...
36:
Wait, you're burning up! We should
get you to a hospital—
41:
Name's Hopper. You can forget
about the hospital—it's bound to be
packed since everything else is
offline.
43:
I've got other business we can
discuss though.
49:
*sigh* Appreciate the help. Wouldn't
have made it without you,
considering how messed up my
motor systems are...
52:
It's small, but it's cozy. Make
yourselves at home.
56:
I'm sorry, but we won't be staying.
You can find someone else for this
business of yours.
61:
Curious. I thought you brought me
here because you were interested in
a reward.
63:
Ah... You don't think I can pay up, do
you? I can download a transaction
service if you don't trust me. What'll
it be: Noxel or AltMeme?
67:
That's not the problem. With the
town in such dire straits, now is not
the time to be discussing private
jobs.
71:
Huh... You folks are pretty weird. First,
this guy's the smallest organic I've
ever seen...
73:
And now, this mutant is talking like
he cares about what's happening
out there.
77:
In that case, what if I told you this
business of mine is related to the
disease spreading throughout town?
85:
So you're sayin' someone's
spreading it around on purpose?
88:
Yep, but luckily for you lot, the virus
won't affect anybody still a hundred
percent organic. In other words: it
only targets bionics.
90:
I've already figured out what he's
after. Nearly had him too, but, well...
You see how I ended up.
93:
That's where you come in—fully
organic flesh bags capable of doing
the heavy lifting.
98:
If this will put a stop to the suffering,
then by all means.
120:
Giving myself the bootleg version of
the trial vaccine.
124:
You had medicine the whole time?
Why didn't you use it in the first
place?
128:
I just said it's a bootleg version. I
couldn't let myself be caught with it.
Besides...
132:
You wouldn't have given me the
time of day if I hadn't tugged on
your heart strings first, right?
138:
No wonder the message was so
hard to track. You broadcast it
through a wired network.
140:
But it's too bad. Troubleshooters are
used to going through junk, so it was
only a matter of time before the jig
was up.
144:
Anyway, that's the line you used to
spread the virus, yeah?
146:
Better fess up if you know what's
good for you.
157:
Guess the clock ran out on the
vaccine... Losing my motor functions
again... *cough*
161:
Thought you got shot for a second
there, geez!
165:
Ahaha... Sorry. You mind taking the
culprit in? I think I've reached my
limit.
172:
Thanks for the help. I'm all better
now that I've got the actual vaccine
in my system. Here's the payment I
promised!
181: Eh, I threw in a little extra.
185:
Tell me, who are you people really?
You're no run-of-the-mill organics,
that much I figured out.
188:
I'm not accusing you of anything.
Just want to know what you'll be
doing after this, and if I can get a
piece of the action too.
192:
Somehow I don't believe that's ALL
you want...
196:
By the way, Alk, you accepted the
credits, right? That's everything in
your hands?
201: Huh? Yeah, it is, and it's way—
211:
I told you I'd download a transaction
service, didn't I? Anyway, deal's
made!
216:
Don't both parties need to agree for
one to count?!
220: Not in my line of business, no.
224:
Look forward to working with you,
Alk. I think we'll make great partners.
